BoostHub.sol
Snapshot Space ID Assembly May Read Uninitialized Memory for Short Strings
The `_snapshotSpaceId` function uses inline assembly to convert a string to a `bytes32` ID. The assembly reads 32 bytes starting from the data portion of the string in memory. For strings shorter than 32 bytes, the remaining bytes in the 32-byte word will contain whatever was in memory at that location (typically zeros in Solidity's memory model, but not guaranteed). The function correctly limits strings to 31 bytes, but the assembly `mload(add(spaceBytes, 32))` reads from the ABI-encoded memory layout where `spaceBytes` points to the length-prefixed bytes array. The data starts at `add(spaceBytes, 32)` (after the length word). For a string of length N < 32, bytes N through 31 of the loaded word will be the bytes immediately following the string data in memory, which in Solidity's memory model are typically zero-padded but could theoretically contain other data.


